<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-pop-doomsday" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Doomsday vs Extinction</title>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       INTRO PROSE
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

  <p>
    In the previous page we solved the logistic equation <m>\dfrac{dP}{dt} = kP(M-P)</m>
    with <m>k \gt 0</m> and found beautifully predictable behavior: no matter where the
    population starts, it always levels off at the carrying capacity <m>M</m>. Now we ask
    what happens when <m>k \lt 0</m>. The formula for the general solution looks almost
    identical, but the behavior is shockingly different, and it depends heavily on the
    initial condition. Our goal here is not to dwell on the algebra of solving, but to
    understand what the solutions actually <em>do</em>, because this will motivate
    everything in the next section.
  </p>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       OBSERVATION: RECAP
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

  <observation xml:id="obs-general-solution-recap">
    <title>General Solution (from previous page)</title>
    <p>
      For the equation <m>\dfrac{dP}{dt} = kP(M - P)</m>, the general solution is
      <me>P(t) = \frac{M}{1 + Ce^{-kMt}},</me>
      where <m>C</m> is an arbitrary constant, and the solution <m>P(t) = 0</m> must
      be noted separately. When <m>k \gt 0</m>, every solution satisfies
      <me>\lim_{t \to \infty} P(t) = M.</me>
    </p>
  </observation>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       ACTIVITY
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

  <activity xml:id="act-doomsday-extinction">
    <title>Doomsday vs Extinction</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Consider the following situation: the birth rate of a population <m>P</m> is
        proportional to <m>P</m> with proportionality constant 2, the death rate is
        the constant 20, and time is measured in years.
        Let's solve the ODE and determine the long-term behavior of the solutions.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <!-- ── TASK A: SETUP AND GENERAL SOLUTION WITH C ── -->

    <task xml:id="task-doom-setup">
      <title>Setting Up and the General Solution</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Using <m>\dfrac{dP}{dt} = \beta P - \alpha P</m> with <m>\beta = 2P</m>
          and <m>\alpha = 20</m>:
          <me>\frac{dP}{dt} = (2P)P - 20P = -2P(10 - P).</me>
          This is <m>kP(M-P)</m> with
          <me>\frac{dP}{dt} = \underbrace{-2}_{k}\,P\!\left(\underbrace{10}_{M} - P\right).</me>
          Since the work is almost identical to the previous page, the general solution is
          <me>P(t) = \frac{10}{1 + Ce^{20t}},</me>
          where we have used <m>-kM = -(-2)(10) = 20</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <!-- ── TASK B: PUT IN TERMS OF P0 ── -->

    <task xml:id="task-doom-initial">
      <title>Writing the Solution in Terms of <m>P_0 = P(0)</m></title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          We will find that the initial value <m>P(0) = P_0</m> makes a huge difference
          on the long-term behavior, so we will put the previous expression for <m>P(t)</m>
          in terms of <m>P_0</m>. We find:
          <me>P(t) = \frac{10 P_0}{P_0 + (10 - P_0)\,e^{20t}}.</me>
        </p>
        <solution>
          <title>Putting <m>C</m> in terms of <m>P_0</m> (can skim for now)</title>
          <p>
            Plugging <m>t = 0</m> into <m>P(t) = \dfrac{10}{1 + Ce^{20t}}</m>:
            <me>P_0 = \frac{10}{1 + C} \implies C = \frac{10}{P_0} - 1 = \frac{10 - P_0}{P_0}.</me>
            Substituting back:
            <me>P(t) = \frac{10}{1 + \frac{10 - P_0}{P_0}e^{20t}} = \frac{10P_0}{P_0 + (10 - P_0)e^{20t}}.</me>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <!-- ── TASK C: STATE TWO CASES ── -->

    <task xml:id="task-doom-two-cases">
      <title>Two Initial Conditions</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          We will examine what happens with the following two initial conditions.
          Recall that in this ODE, <m>M = 10</m>. We will see that the two solutions
          behave much differently, and it actually comes down to whether
          <m>P(0)</m> is less than or greater than <m>M</m>.
        </p>
        <p>
          Plugging in each initial condition:
          <ul>
            <li><p>
              <m>P(0) = 8</m>: <m>\quad\displaystyle P(t) = \frac{80}{8 + 2e^{20t}}</m>
            </p></li>
            <li><p>
              <m>P(0) = 12</m>: <m>\quad\displaystyle P(t) = \frac{120}{12 - 2e^{20t}}</m>
            </p></li>
          </ul>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>

    <!-- ── TASK D: EXTINCTION MC ── -->

    <task xml:id="task-doom-extinction">
      <title><m>P(0) = 8</m>: Extinction</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is <m>\displaystyle\lim_{t \to \infty} P(t)</m> when
          <m>P(t) = \dfrac{80}{8 + 2e^{20t}}</m>?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="no">
        <choice>
          <statement><p><m>10</m></p></statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              That was the logistic case with <m>k \gt 0</m>. Here <m>k \lt 0</m>, so
              the exponent in the solution is positive. As <m>t \to \infty</m>,
              <m>e^{20t} \to \infty</m>, so the denominator blows up, not the numerator.
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement><p><m>\infty</m></p></statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              Not quite. The numerator is the fixed number 80. As <m>t \to \infty</m>,
              <m>e^{20t} \to \infty</m>, so the denominator grows without bound.
              What happens to a fixed numerator over a growing denominator?
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement><p><m>0</m></p></statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              Correct! As <m>t \to \infty</m>, <m>e^{20t} \to \infty</m>, so the
              denominator <m>8 + 2e^{20t} \to \infty</m>, giving
              <m>P(t) = \dfrac{80}{8 + 2e^{20t}} \to 0</m>.
              When <m>P(0) \lt M</m>, the population goes extinct.
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement><p>It depends on <m>C</m>.</p></statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              We have already written the solution in terms of <m>P_0 = P(0) = 8</m>,
              so <m>C</m> is already determined. The limit is a specific number.
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
      </choices>
    </task>

    <!-- ── TASK E: DOOMSDAY MC ── -->

    <task xml:id="task-doom-doomsday">
      <title><m>P(0) = 12</m>: Doomsday</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Now consider <m>P(t) = \dfrac{120}{12 - 2e^{20t}}</m>. Notice something
          strange: the denominator is not always positive. It equals zero when
          <me>12 - 2e^{20t} = 0 \implies e^{20t} = 6 \implies t = T = \frac{\ln 6}{20} \approx 0.09 \text{ years}.</me>
          That is a very short time! As <m>t \to T^-</m> (approaching from the left),
          what happens to <m>P(t)</m>?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <choices randomize="no">
        <choice>
          <statement><p><m>P(t) \to 0</m></p></statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              Not quite. As <m>t \to T^-</m>, the denominator <m>12 - 2e^{20t}</m>
              approaches zero from the positive side. Think about what happens to
              a positive numerator divided by a denominator that approaches <m>0^+</m>.
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement><p><m>P(t) \to 10</m></p></statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              That was the logistic behavior for <m>k \gt 0</m>. Here the denominator
              is heading toward zero, not toward a nonzero number.
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice correct="yes">
          <statement><p><m>P(t) \to +\infty</m></p></statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              Correct! As <m>t \to T^-</m>, the denominator <m>12 - 2e^{20t} \to 0^+</m>,
              so <m>P(t) = \dfrac{120}{12 - 2e^{20t}} \to +\infty</m>.
              The population explodes to infinity in the finite time <m>T \approx 0.09</m> years.
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
        <choice>
          <statement><p><m>P(t) \to -\infty</m></p></statement>
          <feedback>
            <p>
              The numerator 120 is positive. As long as <m>t \lt T</m>, the denominator
              is also positive and approaching <m>0^+</m>. So the quotient goes to
              <m>+\infty</m>, not <m>-\infty</m>.
            </p>
          </feedback>
        </choice>
      </choices>
    </task>

  </activity>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       POST-ACTIVITY: DOOMSDAY PROSE + GRAPH PLACEHOLDERS
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

  <p>
    In finite time <m>T = \dfrac{\ln 6}{20}</m> years, the population explodes to infinity.
    When applying this to population modelling, the model completely breaks down at <m>t = T</m>.
    We call this <term>doomsday</term>: a population explosion in finite time.
  </p>

  <p>
    Let's explore what is happening with these two limits in the graph below. You can change
    the value <m>P(0)</m> and press play to see how the population changes with time. 
    Notice how dramatically different the behavior
    is, even though the ODE is the same and the initial conditions differ by only a small amount
    relative to <m>M = 10</m>. 
  </p>

 <figure xml:id="fig-doomsday-extinction">
  <caption>
    Solutions to <m>\dfrac{dP}{dt} = -2P(10-P)</m> for different initial populations.
    Use the slider to set <m>P(0)</m> and press Play to watch the solution evolve.
    When <m>P(0) \lt M = 10</m>, the population goes extinct.
    When <m>P(0) \gt M = 10</m>, the population explodes to infinity in finite time <m>T</m>
    (marked by the vertical dashed line).
    When <m>P(0) = M</m>, the population stays constant forever.
  </caption>
  <interactive xml:id="interactive-doomsday"
    iframe="ch2-graph/interactive-doomsday.html" width="100%" aspect="4:3">
    <static>
      <p>
        Animated solution curves for <m>\dfrac{dP}{dt} = -2P(10-P)</m> with slider
        for <m>P(0)</m> from 0 to 13. Dashed lines mark the equilibrium solutions
        <m>P = 0</m> and <m>P = 10</m>. When <m>P(0) \lt 10</m>, the solution
        decays to zero (extinction). When <m>P(0) \gt 10</m>, the solution blows up
        to infinity at a finite doomsday time <m>T</m>, marked by a vertical dashed
        line. The model breaks down for <m>t \gt T</m>.
        When <m>P(0) = 10</m>, the population remains at the equilibrium <m>M = 10</m>.
      </p>
    </static>
  </interactive>
</figure>
  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       CONCLUSION OBSERVATION
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

  <observation xml:id="obs-doomsday-extinction-summary">
    <title>Summary: Long-Term Behavior of <m>\dfrac{dP}{dt} = kP(M-P)</m></title>
    <p>
      <ul>
        <li><p>
          <m>k \gt 0</m> (the logistic equation):
          <m>\displaystyle\lim_{t \to \infty} P(t) = M</m> for any <m>P(0) \gt 0</m>.
          The population always levels off at the carrying capacity.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          <m>k \lt 0</m> and <m>P(0) \lt M</m>:
          <m>\displaystyle\lim_{t \to \infty} P(t) = 0</m>.
          The population goes <term>extinct</term>.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          <m>k \lt 0</m> and <m>P(0) \gt M</m>: the population reaches
          <m>+\infty</m> in finite time. This is <term>doomsday</term>.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          <m>P(0) = M</m>: the population is already at the equilibrium solution
          <m>P(t) = M</m> and stays there forever.
        </p></li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </observation>

  <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
       VIDEO
       ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

